body:
**Do you want to request a *feature* or report a *bug*?**
Bug

**What is the current behavior?**
Context consumers not updating while running dev server. They work fine after building/bundling.

**Minimal example (proprietary software, can't paste full example**

Root class (where the context is defined)
```js
export const UserContext = React.createContext();
```
```js
render() {
    console.log(this.state.user);
    return (
      <div>
        <UserContext.Provider value={this.state.user}>
          {this.props.children}
        </UserContext.Provider>
      </div>
    );
  }
```

Consumer file:
```js
<UserContext.Consumer>
  {user => {
    console.log("consumer", user);
    const { isLoggedIn, login, role } = user;
    // Do stuff
  }}
</UserContext.Consumer>
```
**What is the expected behavior?**

When triggering changes to `this.state.user` (logout for example), the new state is updated and logged in the console.log at the beginning of the render, but **it does not propagate the change to the consumer** at all (i.e. the console.log in the consumer code, only gets executed once)

This **only happens in development**.


**Which versions of React, and which browser / OS are affected by this issue? Did this work in previous versions of React?**
The above code has been **working perfectly** for months **until 16.5.2**.

When we recently upgraded to **16.6.0, it stopped working only in development**, it works fine after building. (we use Webpack to build the bundle, no special configuration)

**Note**
Nothing has changed at all in the dev/build configuration, nor anything in the provider/consumer codes.
